==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Recreant
<hw>Rec"re*ant</hw> <pr>(-<it>a</it>nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF.,
cowardly, fr. <ets>recroire</ets>, <ets>recreire</ets>, to forsake,
leave, tire, discourage, regard as conquered, LL. <ets>recredere
se</ets> to declare one's self conquered in combat; hence, those are
called <ets>recrediti</ets> or <ets>recreanti</ets> who are considered
infamous; L. pref. <ets>re-</ets> again, back + <ets>credere</ets> to
believe, to be of opinion; hence, originally, to disavow one's opinion.
See <er>Creed</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Crying for mercy, as a
combatant in the trial by battle; yielding; cowardly; mean-spirited;
craven.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧This <xex>recreant</xex> knight.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Apostate; false; unfaithful.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who, for so many benefits received,⟦br⟧
Turned <qex>recreant</qex> to God, ingrate and false.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recreant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Recreant
<hw>Rec"re*ant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who yields in combat, and
begs for mercy; a mean-spirited, cowardly wretch.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You are all <qex>recreants</qex> and dastards!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

